To create a slider that displays one image on the left and progressively reveals a second image as you move to the right, you can use HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. Here's a simple implementation:

HTML:
```html
<div class="slider-container">
  <div class="slider">
    <div class="image left-image"></div>
    <div class="image right-image"></div>
  </div>
</div>
```

CSS:
```css
.slider-container {
  width: 300px; /* Adjust the width as needed */
  overflow: hidden;
}

.slider {
  display: flex;
  transition: transform 0.3s ease-in-out;
}

.image {
  width: 100%;
  height: 200px; /* Adjust the height as needed */
  background-size: cover;
}

.left-image {
  background-image: url('first-image.jpg'); /* Replace with your image URL */
}

.right-image {
  background-image: url('second-image.jpg'); /* Replace with your image URL */
  transform: translateX(100%);
}
```

JavaScript:
```javascript
const slider = document.querySelector('.slider');
let isRight = false;

slider.addEventListener('mousemove', (e) => {
  if (isRight) return;
  const offsetX = e.clientX - slider.getBoundingClientRect().left;
  const percentage = (offsetX / slider.clientWidth) * 100;
  slider.style.transform = `translateX(${percentage}%)`;

  if (percentage >= 50) {
    isRight = true;
    slider.style.transform = 'translateX(100%)';
  }
});

slider.addEventListener('mouseleave', () => {
  if (!isRight) {
    slider.style.transform = 'translateX(0%)';
  }
});

slider.addEventListener('transitionend', () => {
  if (isRight) {
    slider.style.transition = 'none';
    slider.style.transform = 'translateX(0%)';
    setTimeout(() => {
      slider.style.transition = 'transform 0.3s ease-in-out';
    });
  }
});
```

This code creates a slider with two images, and as you move the mouse cursor from left to right, it progressively reveals the second image. It's a basic implementation that you can enhance and style according to your needs.
